introduction.html.title: Introduction
introduction.html.body:
Introduction
This document describes the preparations for using the Atlas 200 developer kit （DK） to run AI apps, including preparing the SD card, as well as managing the basic information about the developer board and configuring the cross compilation environment on Mind Studio.

board-precautions.html.title: Board Precautions
board-precautions.html.body:
Board Precautions

Before powering the board on, ensure that the Atlas 200 AI acceleration module is properly installed. Otherwise, the board cannot be powered on properly.
Do not remove the case. If the board has to be exposed in special scenarios, do not touch the AI acceleration module and power module of Atlas 200 without protection.
When using a non-standard power adapter, ensure that the power supply range and power meet the board requirements.
The signal level is 3.3 V. When using the interfaces, pay attention to the level matching. Otherwise, the board may be damaged.
The 40-pin extension header does not have strict ESD protection design. Avoid static electricity and do not insert or remove it without disconnecting the power supply.

Figure  1  Atlas 200 DK usage process

（optional）-removing-the-upper-case.html.title: （Optional） Removing the Upper Case
（optional）-removing-the-upper-case.html.body:
（Optional） Removing the Upper Case

 NOTE:Perform this operation when you need to use the camera or an internal interface.  


Check whether a camera cable is lead out from the Atlas 200 DK.

If yes, go to  3.
If no, go to  2.


If no camera cable is lead out from the Atlas 200 DK, pull the plastic latch upwards to loosen the upper case, as shown in  Figure 1.
Figure  1  Removing the upper case - 1

If a camera cable is lead out from the Atlas 200 DK, insert a flat-head screwdriver into the groove between the upper case and the bottom plate, and rotate the screwdriver to pry off the upper case, as shown in （1） in  Figure 2.
Figure  2  Removing the upper case - 2

Remove the upper case.

preparing-the-sd-card.html.title: Preparing the SD Card
preparing-the-sd-card.html.body:
Preparing the SD Card
You can create a system boot disk for the Atlas 200 DK developer board by using the SD card preparation function.
An SD card can be prepared in either of the following ways:

If a card reader is available, insert an SD card into the card reader, connect the card reader to the USB port on the PC where Mind Studio is installed, and then prepare the SD card on Mind Studio.
If no card reader is available, insert the SD card into the card slot of the Atlas 200 DK developer board to connect to the pins of the developer board through the jumper, connect the developer board to the PC where Mind Studio is installed, and then prepare the SD card on Mind Studio.

 NOTE:After the SD card is prepared, Mind Studio automatically creates the default user  HwHiAiUser  that runs applications.  


Environment Preparation  

SD Card

environment-preparation.html.title: Environment Preparation
environment-preparation.html.body:
Environment Preparation
Hardware Environment

Prepare a 16 GB or larger SD card.

 NOTE:The card will be formatted. Back up the data in advance.  


If a card reader is available:

Insert the SD card into the card reader and connect the card reader to the USB port of the PC where Mind Studio is installed.
Run the  fdisk -l  command on the host where Mind Studio is located to check the card reader, for example,  /dev/sda.
Perform  SD Card. Select the device corresponding to the card reader.


If no card reader is available:

Remove the upper case by referring to  （Optional） Removing the Upper Case.
Place the jumper over the following two pins on the developer board as shown in  Figure 1.

 NOTE:Perform this operation when the developer board is powered off. For details about the power-off requirements, see  Powering off the Atlas 200 DK Developer Board.  

Figure  1  Pin map of the developer board

Insert the SD card into the SD card slot of the developer board, and connect the developer board to the USB port of the PC where Mind Studio is installed.

Power on the developer board. For details, see  Powering on the Atlas 200 DK Developer Board.
Perform  SD Card. Select the device corresponding to the USB device.
Run the  fdisk -l  command on the host where Mind Studio is located to check the USB device, for example,  /dev/sda.

local-preparation.html.title: Local Preparation
local-preparation.html.body:
Local Preparation
Preparing the Environment

The Linux server （server where Mind Studio is located） connected to the SD card in USB mode is connected to the network.

Before preparing the SD card, ensure that the qemu-user-static, binfmt-support, YAML, and cross compiler have been installed on the Linux server where Mind Studio is located.
If the Linux server has been connected to the network, run the following commands to install them:
su - root
apt-get install qemu-user-static binfmt-support python3-yaml gcc-aarch64-linux-gnu g++-aarch64-linux-gnu
If the Linux server is not connected to the network, download the sources yourself and install them.


Obtaining Software Packages

Obtain the SD card preparation scripts  make_sd_card.py,  make_ubuntu_sd.sh, the Mini package, and the Ubuntu package.
Table 1  shows the download information.
Table  1  Software packages

Package

Name

Description



Entry script for preparing the SD card

make_sd_card.py

Obtain it from the tools repository at https://github.com/Ascend.


Script for preparing the SD card OS

make_ubuntu_sd.sh

Obtain it from the tools repository at https://github.com/Ascend.


Mini package

mini_developerkit-xxx.rar
The corresponding software integrity verification file is mini_developerkit-xxx.rar.asc.

Software package of the developer board
Obtain the software from the ascenddk-private repository in https://github.com/Ascend.
Verify the software integrity of the downloaded software package by referring to Verifying Software Package Integrity.


Ubuntu package

ubuntu-xxx-server-arm64.iso
 NOTE: xxx indicates the version number.


On Linux, the Ubuntu version must be 16.04.3.
Download the software of the required version from http://old-releases.ubuntu.com/releases/16.04.3/ and install the software.
 NOTE: Ubuntu must be a server-arm64 version.The Ubuntu version must be the same as the Ubuntu version where Mind Studio is installed.







 NOTE:After the software is downloaded, keep their names unchanged.If you want to download a single file from GitHub, right-click  Raw and choose  Save link as from the shortcut menu.  



Procedure

Upload  make_sd_card.py,  make_ubuntu_sd.sh, the Mini package, and the Ubuntu package obtained from  Obtaining Software Packages  to any directory on the server where Mind Studio is located, for example,  /home/ascend/mksd.

 NOTE:The preceding scripts and software packages must be stored in the same directory.Only the software package of one version can be stored in the current directory.  


Switch to the  root user and go to the  /home/ascend/mksd  directory where the card creation script is stored.
su - root
cd /home/ascend/mksd/

（Optional） Modify  NETWORK_CARD_DEFAULT_IP  and  USB_CARD_DEFAULT_IP  in the  make_sd_card.py  file to change the IP address of developer board. The default IP address of the developer board is 192.168.1.2 in USB connection mode and is 192.168.0.2 in network cable connection mode.

Run the  make_sd_card.py  script.
Run the  fdisk -l  command to query the name of the USB device where the SD card is located, for example,  /dev/sda.
Run the  make_sd_card.py  script:
python3 make_sd_card.py local /dev/sda

local  indicates that the SD card is prepared locally.
/dev/sda  is the name of the USB device where the SD card is located.

If  Figure 1  is displayed, the card is successfully prepared.
Figure  1  Message indicating successful SD card preparation

 NOTE:If the card preparation fails, check the log files in the sd_card_making_log  folder in the current directory.  


（Optional） Remove the jumper.

 NOTE:If no card reader is available, remove the jumper cap after the SD card is prepared.

（optional）-powering-on-the-atlas-200-dk..title: （Optional） Powering On the Atlas 200 DK
（optional）-powering-on-the-atlas-200-dk..body:
（Optional） Powering On the Atlas 200 DK
If no card reader is used and the Atlas 200 DK has been powered on before the SD card is made, skip this section.
If a card reader is used to prepare the SD card, insert the SD card into the Atlas 200 DK card slot before powering the Atlas 200 DK on.
For details about how to power on the Atlas 200 DK, see  Powering on the Atlas 200 DK Developer Board.

 NOTE:Do not power off the Atlas 200 DK while it is booting for the first time. Otherwise, the Atlas 200 DK may be damaged. To re-power on the Atlas 200 DK, wait at least 2s after it is powered off.

connecting-the-atlas-200-dk-to-the-ui-ho.title: Connecting the Atlas 200 DK to the UI Host
connecting-the-atlas-200-dk-to-the-ui-ho.body:
Connecting the Atlas 200 DK to the UI Host
This topic describes how to connect the Atlas 200 DK developer board to the server where Mind Studio is located.
The Atlas 200 DK developer board can be connected to Mind Studio through a USB cable or network cable, as shown in  Figure 1.
Figure  1  Connection between the Atlas 200 DK developer board and Mind Studio
Procedure

Connect Mind Studio to the Atlas 200 DK developer board.
There are two connection modes:

To connect to the Atlas 200 DK developer board over the USB port, go to  2.
To connect to the Atlas 200 DK developer board through a network cable over the router or switch, go to  3.


In the USB connection scenario, configure the IP address of the server where Mind Studio is located.
Change the IP address of the server to  192.168.1.x  （The value ranges of  x  is 0–1 and 3–255）.

 NOTE:The default IP address of the Atlas 200 DK developer board is  192.168.1.2. USB 2.0 and USB 3.0 are both supported.  

When connecting to the Atlas 200 DK developer board over the USB port, you need to configure the static USB IP address. The following describes how to configure the static IP address by using the script or manually:

Configuration by using the script

Download  configure_usb_ethernet.sh from  https://github.com/Ascend/tools/blob/master/configure_usb_ethernet.sh  to any directory on the Ubuntu server where Mind Studio is located, for example,  /home/ascend/config_usb_ip/.

 NOTE:If you want to download a single file from GitHub, right-click  Raw and choose  Save link as  from the shortcut menu.  


Go to the directory where the script for configuring the USB IP address is located as the  root user, for example,  /home/ascend/config_usb_ip.

Run the following command to configure the USB IP address:

bash configure_usb_ethernet.sh**-s** ip_address
Use the specified IP address to configure the static IP address of the USB network adapter in the system. If  bash configure_usb_ethernet.sh  is run, the default IP address  192.168.1.166  is used.

If multiple USB network adapters exist, run the  ifconfig  command to query the name of the USB network adapter, and then run the following command to configure the IP address of the specified network adapter:
bash configure_usb_ethernet.sh -s usb_nic_name ip_address
usb_nic_name: name of the USB network adapter 
ip_address: specified IP address
Example command:
bash configure_usb_ethernet.sh -s enp0s20f0u8 192.168.1.236


After the configuration is complete, run the  ifconfig  command to check whether the IP address takes effect.



Manual configuration

Log in to the Mind Studio server as the Mind Studio installation user and run the following command to switch to the  root user:
su - root

Obtain the name of the USB network adapter.
ifconfig -a

Add the static IP address of the USB network adapter to the  /etc/network/interfaces  file.
Run the following command to open the  interfaces  file:
vi /etc/network/interfaces
Configure the  interfaces file as follows. Assume that the USB network adapter is named  enp0s20f0u4  and its static IP address is  192.168.1.134.
auto enp0s20f0u4
iface enp0s20f0u4 inet static
address 192.168.1.134
netmask 255.255.255.0

Modify the  NetworkManager.conf  file to prevent the network configuration from being invalid after restart.
Run the following command to open the  NetworkManager.conf  file:
vi /etc/NetworkManager/NetworkManager.conf
Change  managed=false  to  managed=true  in the file.

Enable the static IP address:
enp0s20f0u4ifdown 
enp0s20f0u4ifup 
service NetworkManager restart





In the network cable connection scenario, configure the IP address of the server where Mind Studio is located.
Change the IP address of the server to  192.168.0.x  （The value ranges of  x  is 0–1 and 3–255）.

 NOTE:The default IP address of the Atlas 200 DK developer board is 192.168.0.2, with a 24-bit subnet mask.  

Perform the following steps:

Log in to the Mind Studio server as the Mind Studio installation user and run the following command to switch to the  root user:
su - root

Add the virtual static IP address to the  /etc/network/interfaces  file.
Run the following command to open the  interfaces  file:
vi /etc/network/interfaces
Configure the  interfaces file. Assume that the network adapter is named  eth0:1  and its static IP address is  192.168.0.134.
auto eth0:1
iface eth0:1 inet static
address 192.168.0.134
netmask 255.255.255.0

Modify the  NetworkManager.conf  file to prevent the network configuration from being invalid after restart.
Run the following command to open the  NetworkManager.conf  file:
vi /etc/NetworkManager/NetworkManager.conf
Change  managed=false  to  managed=true  in the file.

Restart the network services.
service networking restart
service NetworkManager restart




Follow-up Operations
After connecting the Atlas 200 DK developer board to Mind Studio, you can determine whether to restart the Linux server or power off the Atlas 200 DK based on the status of the Atlas 200 DK LED indicators. For details about the status of the LED indicators, see  Table 1.

 NOTICE:Restart or power off the server or developer board with caution, especially when the Atlas 200 DK is being upgraded.

configuring-the-cross-compilation-enviro.title: Configuring the Cross Compilation Environment in the UI Host
configuring-the-cross-compilation-enviro.body:
Configuring the Cross Compilation Environment in the UI Host
Before using the Atlas 200 DK to develop apps, you need to configure the cross compilation environment on the Linux server where Mind Studio is located.

 NOTE:If the Linux server used in  Preparing the SD Card  is the server where Mind Studio connected to the Atlas 200 DK is located, skip this section. During SD card preparation, a cross compilation environment is automatically deployed for the Linux server.  

Prerequisites
Perform the following steps to check whether the cross compilation environment has been deployed:
ls -alF /usr/lib/aarch64-linux-gnu

If the information shown in  Figure 1  is displayed, the cross compilation environment has been configured for the server where Mind Studio is configured. Skip this section.
Figure  1  Message indicating the cross compilation environment is deployed

If the information shown in  Figure 2  is displayed, the cross compilation environment of the server where Mind Studio is located is not configured. In this case, manually configure the cross compilation environment as follows.
Figure  2  Message indicating the cross compilation environment is not deployed


Procedure

Obtain the  make_ui_cross_env.py  script for configuring the cross compilation environment.
Obtain it from the  tools repository at  https://github.com/Ascend.

Upload the  make_ui_cross_env.py  script to any directory on the server where Mind Studio is located, for example,  /home/ascend/mkuicross.

Switch to the  root user and go to the  /home/ascend/mkuicross  directory where the  make_ui_cross_env.py  script is located:
su - root
cd /home/ascend/mkuicross/

Run the following command to install Pexpect:
pip3 install pexpect

Run the  make_ui_cross_env.py  script:
python3 make_ui_cross_env.py
The following information is displayed:
Atlas DK Development Board IP: IP address of the Atlas 200 DK developer board IP
Atlas DK Development Board SSH user: SSH login user name of the Atlas 200 DK developer board. Set this parameter to the common user. The default user name is  HwHiAiUser.
Atlas DK Development Board SSH user password: password of the SSH login user of the Atlas 200 DK developer board
Atlas DK Development Board SSH port: SSH port number of the Atlas 200 DK developer board. The default value is  22.

If the Mind Studio server has been connected to the network:
During the script execution, the cross-compilers gcc-aarch64-linux-gnu and g++-aarch64-linux-gnu are downloaded and installed on the Linux server where Mind Studio is located.  Figure 3  shows the execution result.
Figure  3  Configuring a Cross Compilation Environment

If the Mind Studio server is not connected to the network, the message shown in  Figure 4  is displayed. 
Figure  4  Message indicating cross compilers fail to be downloaded
If the message shown in  Figure 4  is displayed:

If the cross compilers gcc-aarch64-linux-gnu and g++-aarch64-linux-gnu have been deployed in the system, enter  Y  to continue the deployment of the cross compilation environment.
If the cross compilers gcc-aarch64-linux-gnu and g++-aarch64-linux-gnu are not deployed in the system, enter any other keys to exit the script, manually download and install the cross compilers, and then run the  python3 make_ui_cross_env.py  command.

changing-the-password.html.title: Changing the Password
changing-the-password.html.body:
Changing the Password
Before using the Atlas 200 DK developer board, you need to change the initial user password.
Changing the Password of a Common User
HwHiAiUser is the default user created during SD card preparation on Mind Studio. The default password is  Mind@123. After the Atlas 200 DK developer board is successfully connected to Mind Studio, you need to change the initial password of the  HwHiAiUser user.

Log in to the Atlas 200 DK developer board as the  HwHiAiUser  user in SSH mode on the Mind Studio server.

 NOTE:The default login password of the  HwHiAiUser user is  Mind@123.  


Run the  passwd  command to change the password of the  HwHiAiUser user.
See  Figure 1.
Figure  1  Changing the password of the HwHiAiUser user


Modifying the Password of the Root User

Log in to the Atlas 200 DK developer board as the  HwHiAiUser  user in SSH mode on the Mind Studio server.

 NOTE:The default login password of the  HwHiAiUser user is  Mind@123.  


Run the following command to switch to the  root  user:
su - root

 NOTE:The default login password of the  root user is  Mind@123.  


Run the  passwd  command to change the password of the  root user, as shown in  Figure 2.
Figure  2  Changing the password of the root user

adding-the-atlas-200-dk-to-mind-studio.h.title: Adding the Atlas 200 DK to Mind Studio
adding-the-atlas-200-dk-to-mind-studio.h.body:
Adding the Atlas 200 DK to Mind Studio
You can use the function of Atlas 200 DK configuration management provided by Mind Studio to detect the connection status of the Atlas 200 DK and modify the device information.

 NOTE:The current configuration management function supports only single-user and single-task scenarios. It does not support multi-user and multi-task scenarios.  

Adding a Device

On the menu bar of Mind Studio, choose  Tools > Atlas DK Configuration.
The  Atlas DK Configuration  dialog box is displayed, as shown in  Figure 1.
Figure  1  Atlas DK Configuration

Click  Add.
The device information dialog box is displayed.

Configure the basic information about the Atlas 200 DK to be added.
See  Figure 2.
Figure  2  Device information dialog box
The configuration parameters are described as follows:

Device Name: device name, which can be customized
Com Mode: communication mode, which is  NIC or  USB

NIC indicates the network communication mode.
USB indicates using a USB virtual network adapter.


IP Address: IP address of the Atlas 200 DK device



Click  Save.
After the configuration is complete, the Atlas 200 DK Status Check dialog box as shown in  Figure 3  is displayed, displaying the status of each module.
Figure  3  Atlas DK Status Check dialog box
The parameters are described as follows:

Connection: communication status between Mind Studio and the Atlas 200 DK
Media Drive: status of the audio and video processing module
Camera1: whether channel 1 is connected to a camera
Camera2: whether channel 2 is connected to a camera


 NOTE:   

During device addition, the network connection between the PC and the Atlas 200 DK device is checked. If the network connection is normal, the configuration information of the Atlas 200 DK device is added to the  Atlas DK Configuration  device list. Otherwise, a message is displayed indicating that the connection fails and the device configuration information is not added to the  Atlas DK Configuration  device list.  
If a USB virtual network adapter is used for communication, the IP address of Mind Studio must be the default setting  192.168.1.2  and the IP address of the USB virtual network adapter on the PC must be on the same network segment as  192.168.1.2. The default subnet mask is  255.255.255.0. You may also use the terminal software （such as Xshell） to access a system terminal of the Atlas 200 DK device by using an NIC or USB virtual network adapter.  




Connecting a Device
Select the device to be operated from the  Atlas DK Configuration  device list, and click  Connect, as shown in  Figure 4.
Figure  4  Connecting a device
For details about the description of the parameters, see  Adding a Device.

changing-the-atlas-200-dk-ip-address.htm.title: Changing the Atlas 200 DK IP Address
changing-the-atlas-200-dk-ip-address.htm.body:
Changing the Atlas 200 DK IP Address
If multiple Atlas 200 DK developer boards are configured, using the default IP address my cause conflicts. You can change their IP addresses on Mind Studio.

 NOTE:This topic describes how to modify the IP address of an Atlas 200 DK device on Mind Studio in the network cable connection mode.For the USB connection mode, you need to modify the  /etc/network/interfaces  file on the device background, and then run the  service networking restart command to restart the network service.  

Procedure

On the menu bar of Mind Studio, choose  Tools > Atlas DK Configuration.
The  Atlas DK Configuration  dialog box is displayed.

In the  Atlas DK Configuration  dialog box that is displayed, select the device, and click  IP Modify.
See  Figure 1.
Figure  1  Atlas DK Configuration device list

In the  Device IP Modify  dialog box that is displayed, configure the IP address of the Atlas 200 DK device.
See  Figure 2.
Figure  2  Device IP Modify dialog box
Enter the new IP address, subnet mask, and gateway of the device, and click  Save.

 NOTE:   

Currently, this modification approach is supported only in NIC communication mode.

version-upgrade.html.title: Version Upgrade
version-upgrade.html.body:
Version Upgrade
Upgrade on the Mind Studio GUI
For details about how to upgrade the GUI, see 6 "Version Upgrade" in the  Mind Studio Installation Guide.

 NOTE:Do not power off the Atlas 200 DK developer board during the upgrade. The upgrade takes about 15 minutes.  

Verifying the Upgrade

Log in to the Atlas 200 DK developer board as the  HwHiAiUser  user in SSH mode on the Mind Studio server.
ssh HwHiAiUser@192.168.0.2

 NOTE:Replace  192.168.0.2  with the actual IP address of the developer board.  


Check the version number of the developer board after the upgrade.
cat /etc/sys_version.conf

Query the upgrade logs.
cd /var/davinci/log
cat upgrade.log
cat firmware_upgrade_progress.log
Check whether the upgrade logs contain error information. If no error information is displayed, the upgrade is successful.
If any error information is displayed, connect to the developer board on the Mind Studio GUI to locate the fault. For details about how to use the log tool, see the  Ascend 310 Mind Studio Auxiliary Tools.

powering-on-the-atlas-200-dk-developer-b.title: Powering on the Atlas 200 DK Developer Board
powering-on-the-atlas-200-dk-developer-b.body:
Powering on the Atlas 200 DK Developer Board
Precautions
Do not power off the Atlas 200 DK developer board while it is booting for the first time. Otherwise, the developer board may be damaged. To re-power on the developer board, wait at least 2s after it is powered off.
Procedure

Plug in the power cable and connect the power module to the external power supply.  Figure 1  shows the power interface on the Atlas 200 DK. Connect to the power supply, the Atlas 200 DK automatically boots.
Figure  1  Interface diagram

1

Power indicator

2

Power interface


3

USB port

4

MicroSD card


5

Network port

6

Reset key





Check the status of the indicator to ensure that the Atlas 200 DK is powered on properly.
Table 1  describes the LED indicator states.
Table  1  States of the LED indicators

LED4

LED3

Status of the Atlas 200 DK Developer Board 

Precautions

connecting-the-atlas-200-dk-over-the-ser.title: Connecting the Atlas 200 DK over the Serial Port
connecting-the-atlas-200-dk-over-the-ser.body:
Connecting the Atlas 200 DK over the Serial Port
The Atlas 200 DK provides two serial ports for interconnecting with the mini module and 3559 module respectively.  Figure 1  shows the serial port connection diagram.
Figure  1  Serial port connection diagram
Two serial ports are provided: miniD （for Ascend 310） and 3559 (for Hi3559). Connect the serial lanes according to the colors.
For the serial cable, use 1.8 V USB-to-serial cables. The 3.3 V ones are not supported.

managing-the-atlas-200-dk-device.html.title: Managing the Atlas 200 DK Device
managing-the-atlas-200-dk-device.html.body:
Managing the Atlas 200 DK Device
Mind Studio provides the functions of adding, modifying, deleting, and connecting Atlas 200 DK devices, and modifying their IP addresses.

 NOTE:The current configuration management function supports only single-user and single-task scenarios. It does not support multi-user and multi-task scenarios.  

Portal
On the menu bar of Mind Studio, choose  Tools > Atlas DK Configuration, as shown in  Figure 1.
Figure  1  Atlas DK Configuration
Adding a Device

On the menu bar of Mind Studio, choose  Tools > Atlas DK Configuration.
The  Atlas DK Configuration  dialog box is displayed, as shown in  Figure 2.
Figure  2  Atlas DK Configuration

Click  Add.
The device information dialog box is displayed.

Configure the basic information about the Atlas 200 DK to be added.
See  Figure 3.
Figure  3  Device information dialog box
The configuration parameters are described as follows:

Device Name: device name, which can be customized
Com Mode: communication mode, which is  NIC or  USB

NIC indicates the network communication mode.
USB indicates using a USB virtual network adapter.


IP Address: IP address of the Atlas 200 DK device



Click  Save.
After the configuration is complete, the Atlas 200 DK Status Check dialog box as shown in  Figure 4  is displayed, displaying the status of each module.
Figure  4  Atlas DK Status Check dialog box
The parameters are described as follows:

Connection: communication status between Mind Studio and the Atlas 200 DK
Media Drive: status of the audio and video processing module
Camera1: whether channel 1 is connected to a camera
Camera2: whether channel 2 is connected to a camera


 NOTE:   

During device addition, the network connection between the PC and the Atlas 200 DK device is checked. If the network connection is normal, the configuration information of the Atlas 200 DK device is added to the  Atlas DK Configuration  device list. Otherwise, a message is displayed indicating that the connection fails and the device configuration information is not added to the  Atlas DK Configuration  device list.  
If a USB virtual network adapter is used for communication, the IP address of Mind Studio must be the default setting  192.168.1.2  and the IP address of the USB virtual network adapter on the PC must be on the same network segment as  192.168.1.2. The default subnet mask is  255.255.255.0. You may also use the terminal software （such as Xshell） to access a system terminal of the Atlas 200 DK device by using an NIC or USB virtual network adapter.  




Modifying a Device
Select a device from the  Atlas DK Configuration  device list. Otherwise, the  Modify option is unavailable, as shown in  Figure 5.
Figure  5  Atlas DK Configuration dialog box
Select the device to be modified, click  Modify  to modify the device configuration information, and click  Save, as shown in  Figure 6.
Figure  6  Modifying the Atlas DK configuration 
Deleting a Device
Select a device from the  Atlas DK Configuration  device list. Otherwise, the  Delete button is unavailable, as shown in  Figure 5.
Select the device to be deleted and click  Delete, as shown in  Figure 7.
Figure  7  Deleting an Atlas DK device
Connecting a Device
Select the device to be operated from the  Atlas DK Configuration  device list, and click  Connect, as shown in  Figure 8.
Figure  8  Connecting a device
For details about the description of the parameters, see  Adding a Device.

verifying-software-package-integrity.htm.title: Verifying Software Package Integrity
verifying-software-package-integrity.htm.body:
Verifying Software Package Integrity
Before installing the software package, check whether the software package is incomplete or damaged due to network or storage device faults.
Upload the obtained  mini_developerkit-xxx.rar  and  mini_developerkit-xxx.rar.asc  files to the home directory of the common user on Linux where the Mind Studio is to be installed.

Configure the opengpg public key. For details, see  Configuring the openpgp Public Key.
Run the following command to check whether the software package is valid and complete, as shown in  Figure 1:
gpg --verify "mini_developerkit-xxx.rar.asc"
Figure  1  Verifying the software package integrity
In the returned information,  27A74824  indicates the public key ID. If the message  Good signature  is displayed without  WARNING or  FAIL, the signature is valid and the integrity verification is passed. If  WARNING or  FAIL is displayed, the verification fails. Rectify the fault by referring to the handling suggestions described in  What Do I Do If a WARNING or FAIL Result Is Returned in the Integrity Verification of a Software Package?.



 NOTE:   

The integrity verification can be performed only when the software package and the .asc file are stored in the same path.

configuring-the-openpgp-public-key.html.title: Configuring the openpgp Public Key
configuring-the-openpgp-public-key.html.body:
Configuring the openpgp Public Key
Prerequisites

Configure the public key as the installation user of Mind Studio.
The GnuPG tool has been installed on Linux.
Verification:

If the GnuPG tool has been installed, run the  gpg --version  command in the shell and the following information is displayed:


If the GnuPG tool is not installed, install the tool by following the instructions provided in  http://www.gnupg.org/, the official website of GnuPG.




Configuring the Public Key

Obtain the public key file.
Go to the  OpenPGP download page  and click the download link, as shown in  Figure 1. The file download page is displayed.
Figure  1  Click to download the file.
The  KEYS  file is the public key file, as shown in  Figure 2.
Figure  2  Selecting the KEYS file

 NOTE:If you want to switch to the English interface, click    in the upper right corner.  


Upload the downloaded  KEYS.txt  file to the Linux OS where Mind Studio is located,
for example,  /home/username/openpgp/keys.

Import the public key file.
Run the following command to go to the directory that contains the public key file  KEYS.
# gpg --import "/home/username/openpgp/keys/KEYS.txt"
Figure  3  Import the public key file.

 NOTE:/home/username/openpgp/keys  indicates the absolute path of the public key file  KEYS. Replace  username  with the name of the Mind Studio installation user.  


Run the following command to view the import result:
# gpg --fingerprint
Figure  4  Checking the import result

Verify the public key.

The validity of the OpenPGP public key must be verified based on the public key ID, fingerprint, UID, and the publisher of the public key. The published information of the OpenPGP public key is as follows:

Public key ID: 27A74824
Key fingerprint: B100 0AC3 8C41 525A 19BD C087 99AD 81DF 27A74824
UID: OpenPGP signature key for Huawei software （created on 30th Dec,2013）support@huawei.com

After the information is verified, you can set the trust level for the public key

Set the trust level for the public key by running the following command:
# gpg --edit-key "OpenPGP signature key for Huawei" trust
Information similar to the following is displayed. Enter  5  after  Your decision?, which indicates  I trust ultimately. Enter  y  after  Do you really want to set this key to ultimate trust? （y/N）.
Figure  5  Setting the trust level for the public key



Run the  quit  command to exit.

what-do-i-do-if-a-redundant-mounted-disk.title: What Do I Do If a Redundant Mounted Disk Appears Due to Manual Removal of the SD Card During SD Card Preparation?
what-do-i-do-if-a-redundant-mounted-disk.body:
What Do I Do If a Redundant Mounted Disk Appears Due to Manual Removal of the SD Card During SD Card Preparation?
If the SD card is manually removed during SD card preparation, a redundant temporarily-mounted disk is generated. You can perform the following steps to remove it:

Log in to the Ubuntu server where Mind Studio is located as the Mind Studio installation user and run the  su - root  command to switch to the  root user.
Run the  df -h  command to view the temporarily mounted  /dev/loop0  disk.
root@kickseed:~# df -h
Filesystem       Size     Used      Avail   Use% Mounted on
/dev/loop0      745M  745M     0        100% /home/ubuntu/studio/scripts/180919002200
/dev/sdc1        118G   60M       112G  1%    /home/ubuntu/studio/scripts/sd_mount_dir

Run the  umount  command to unmount the disk. Replace  /dev/loop0  and  /dev/sdc1  in the commands based on the actual query result in Step  2.
root@kickseed:~# umount /dev/loop0
root@kickseed:~# umount /dev/sdc1
If the message  target is busy  is displayed, restart the Ubuntu PC and repeat Steps  1  to  3.

what-do-i-do-if-a-warning-or-fail-result.title: What Do I Do If a WARNING or FAIL Result Is Returned in the Integrity Verification of a Software Package?
what-do-i-do-if-a-warning-or-fail-result.body:
What Do I Do If a WARNING or FAIL Result Is Returned in the Integrity Verification of a Software Package?
If a WARNING or FAIL result is returned in the integrity verification of a software package, the verification fails. Rectify the fault by referring to the handling suggestions described in  Table 1.
Table  1  Verification result examples

Verification Result Description

Displayed Information

Verification Result

Handling Suggestion



The signature verification is successful without exception.

gpg: Signature made Thu Jan 9 15:29:06 2014 CST using RSA key ID 27A74824
gpg: Good signature from "OpenPGP signature key for Huawei software (created on 30th Dec,2013) "

PASS

N/A


The signature verification fails.

gpg: Signature made Thu Jan 9 15:29:06 2014 CST using RSA key ID 27A74824
gpg: BAD signature from "OpenPGP signature key for Huawei software (created on 30th Dec,2013) "

FAIL

Download the target file again.


The public key cannot be found.

gpg: Signature made Thu Jan 9 15:20:01 2014 CST using RSA key ID 27A74824
gpg: Can't check signature: public key not found

FAIL

Download the public key again. For details, see 9.7 Configuring the openpgp Public Key.


The signature verification is successful, but the public key is not ultimately trusted.

gpg: Signature made Thu Jan 9 15:29:06 2014 CST using RSA key ID 27A74824
gpg: Good signature from "OpenPGP signature key for Huawei software (created on 30th Dec,2013) "
gpg: WARNING: This key is not certified with a trusted signature!
gpg: There is no indication that the signature belongs to the owner.
Primary key fingerprint: B100 0AC3 8C41 525A 19BD C087 99AD 81DF 27A7 4824

WARNING

After confirming that KeyID is 27A74824, set the Huawei public key to ultimate trust. For details, see 9.7 Configuring the openpgp Public Key.


The corresponding source file cannot be found.

gpg: no signed data
gpg: can't hash datafile: No data

Download the target file again.

gpg: Signature made 04/24/13 10:50:29 CST using RSA key ID 133B64E5
gpg: Expired signature from " OpenPGP signature test key "
gpg: Signature expired 04/25/13 10:50:29 CST

Download an updated target file.

gpg: Signature made 06/13/13 11:14:49 CST using RSA key ID 133B64E5
gpg: Good signature from " OpenPGP signature test key "
gpg: WARNING: This key has been revoked by its owner!
gpg: This could mean that the signature is forged.
gpg: reason for revocation: Key is no longer used
gpg: revocation comment:

WARNING

Download the latest public key and an updated target file.
